                <h1>Static Timing Analysis</h1>


                <p>Predict timing without vectors and catch violations early.</p>


            </section>





            <section class="scroll-reveal">


                <h2>What STA Does</h2>


                <p>STA evaluates all timing paths in a design using library models and constraints. It reports setup, hold, and recovery/removal checks without requiring simulation vectors.</p>


                <p>Key outputs include worst negative slack (WNS), total negative slack (TNS), and path-based diagnostics.</p>


            </section>





            <section class="scroll-reveal">


                <h2>Core Concepts</h2>


                <p>Setup checks ensure data arrives before the clock edge.</p>


                <p>Hold checks ensure data remains stable after the clock edge.</p>


                <p>Clock uncertainty, OCV derates, and RC parasitics add realism to signoff.</p>


            </section>





            <section class="scroll-reveal">


                <h2>Practical Checklist</h2>


                <p>Fix setup with faster cells, buffering, or path restructuring.</p>


                <p>Fix hold with delay insertion or clock path tuning.</p>


                <p>Validate constraints and clock definitions before deep optimization.</p>


            </section>





